WEBVTT

00:07.257 --> 00:10.249
[HORN BLARING]

00:12.971 --> 00:14.962
[m1

00:17.351 --> 00:19.467
Hey. Hey, pal.

00:19.686 --> 00:20.971
What's going on?

00:21.146 --> 00:23.182
Everything okay?

00:24.274 --> 00:25.684
You all right?

00:25.859 --> 00:27.520
You a little turned around?

00:27.694 --> 00:30.401
If you're headed to Harrisburg,
you're going the wrong way.

00:30.948 --> 00:32.859
You hear me?

00:47.047 --> 00:48.412
What do you got there?

01:01.353 --> 01:03.344
"Assistant U.S. Attorney"?

01:05.566 --> 01:08.854
He hasn't spoken. The doctors say
he experienced severe trauma.

01:09.027 --> 01:10.312
Where did you find him?

01:10.487 --> 01:13.900
Oh, on a highway outside of Harrisburg.
We're still piecing it together,

01:14.074 --> 01:16.281
but we think he may have
been hitchhiking.

01:16.827 --> 01:18.738
Ma'am? Are you okay?

01:18.912 --> 01:22.154
It's just... It's been 12 years.

01:28.547 --> 01:29.753
Mark?

01:29.923 --> 01:31.584
Mark.

01:32.259 --> 01:33.840
It's me.

01:34.511 --> 01:36.297
It's Donna.

01:40.058 --> 01:41.468
Where have you been?

01:41.685 --> 01:44.518
It's been 12 years.

01:54.615 --> 01:56.606
[CHUCKLES]

02:02.205 --> 02:03.581
Ah.

02:06.752 --> 02:08.367
What is this, a '78?

02:09.796 --> 02:13.163
You got a picture?
My father loved Cadillacs.

02:17.304 --> 02:20.967
And she's alive?
She's calling herself Jolene Parker.

02:21.141 --> 02:24.349
l'll notify you when | find her.
You don't have all the information.

02:24.519 --> 02:26.055
l have all I need.
No. She's--

02:26.229 --> 02:28.311
Do | tell you how to do yourjob?

02:29.066 --> 02:30.522
No, I don't.

02:30.692 --> 02:33.274
So don't tell me how to do mine.

02:34.029 --> 02:35.644
If I was able to find you hiding

02:35.822 --> 02:38.814
on that sheep farm outside
of Dingle, I can find this girl.

02:39.159 --> 02:41.445
Don't you worry how.

02:44.247 --> 02:47.375
I love hats, but that...

02:47.542 --> 02:52.377
Honestly, that takes
a certain kind of man.

02:52.631 --> 02:55.794
What size are you?
Seven and a quarter?

02:55.967 --> 02:57.673
I'm a seven and a half.

03:00.806 --> 03:02.387
I'll find the girl.

03:02.557 --> 03:03.546
[m1

03:03.725 --> 03:06.967
I don't want you to find her,
I know where she is.

03:07.229 --> 03:09.345
I want you to tell me
where she's been.

03:09.856 --> 03:13.019
Cities, safe houses, aliases.

03:13.193 --> 03:15.855
She's already faked her death
to elude me, now she's back.

03:16.029 --> 03:20.068
I want you to tell me everything you can
about where she's been,

03:20.242 --> 03:21.982
what she's been up to.

03:22.160 --> 03:25.072
I thought this was a conference,
not a book burning.

03:25.288 --> 03:28.371
BURT:
There's nothing wrong with
a little editing. They're children.

03:28.542 --> 03:30.533
Kids shouldn't be reading Lolita.
Why not?

03:30.711 --> 03:32.702
I mean, the heart goes
where it wants to go.

03:32.921 --> 03:37.255
Mr. Whitney's heart sent him
right into an affair with
Timmy Logan's morn.

03:37.426 --> 03:38.791
Are you saying
that's okay?

03:39.761 --> 03:41.797
No, ljust—- I don't think books

03:41.972 --> 03:43.007
are anything
to be afraid of.

03:43.181 --> 03:44.170
[PHONE BUZZING]

03:44.349 --> 03:47.432
I think that people have affairs
because they're miserable
in their marriages.

03:47.602 --> 03:49.467
I don't think you should
judge them.

03:49.646 --> 03:52.262
And I certainly don't think
you can blame a book.

03:53.442 --> 03:54.522
What do you think, Tom?

03:55.485 --> 03:57.100
Urn...

03:57.279 --> 03:59.611
I think Mr. Whitney should
thank his lucky stars

03:59.781 --> 04:02.363
because Timmy Logan's mom
is way out of his league.

04:02.534 --> 04:05.241
WOMAN:
Call me provincial,
but I for one think it's inappropriate.

04:05.412 --> 04:08.074
I mean, how old is he anyway?

04:08.248 --> 04:10.455
[BURT & WOMAN
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

04:10.667 --> 04:13.500
[m1

04:15.714 --> 04:16.920
Lizzy.

04:18.049 --> 04:20.005
Have you seen the paper?
What about it?

04:22.179 --> 04:25.171
Mark Hastings,
U.S. Attorney from Maryland.

04:25.348 --> 04:29.216
Twelve years ago, he indicted
the head of the Reynoso cartel.

04:29.394 --> 04:31.055
A week later,
he went missing.

04:31.229 --> 04:33.971
I remember. The Bureau assumed
it was a retribution killing.

04:34.149 --> 04:37.312
Well, two days ago, he was found
wandering on a road in Pennsylvania.

04:37.486 --> 04:39.898
Nobody knows where he's been.
Was he in hiding?

04:40.071 --> 04:43.689
I believe he was held captive,
but not by the Reynoso cartel.

04:43.867 --> 04:47.530
It's all quite a mystery. They say
he's too traumatized to speak.

04:47.704 --> 04:50.286
But if what I believe
about Hastings is true,

04:50.457 --> 04:52.823
if he has been held captive
all these years,

04:53.001 --> 04:55.617
then it would confirm
that the myth is true.

04:55.796 --> 04:58.253
The Judge is real.

04:58.423 --> 05:01.881
The Judge?
Every culture has a justice myth,

05:02.052 --> 05:07.092
an avenging angel who exacts
retribution for the weak and innocent.

05:07.265 --> 05:10.803
Golem for the Jews,
Tu Po for the Chinese,

05:10.977 --> 05:15.516
the ancient Greeks had
Adrasteia the goddess of revenge.

05:15.732 --> 05:17.017
And we have the Judge.

05:17.192 --> 05:20.901
Think of him as a prisoner's
court of last resort.

05:21.112 --> 05:23.444
When your legal appeals
have all been exhausted

05:23.657 --> 05:28.617
and there is no hope left,
you can make one last plea
to the Judge.

05:28.787 --> 05:29.947
What kind of plea?

05:30.121 --> 05:33.363
Prisoners can state their case,
argue their innocence,

05:33.542 --> 05:37.285
explain why they were convicted
unfairly, and who is responsible.

05:37.462 --> 05:39.953
A prosecutor, a corrupt detective,

05:40.131 --> 05:42.087
maybe an incompetent
public defender.

05:42.259 --> 05:44.295
LIZ:
This demand for justice,
where does it go?

05:44.469 --> 05:47.176
RAYMOND:
Supposedly, it's passed
among inmates

05:47.347 --> 05:50.339
until it ﬁnally reaches
some book depository

05:50.517 --> 05:53.475
at the federal penitentiary
in Monroe, Virginia.

05:53.645 --> 05:55.681
LIZ: And then?
RAYMOND: Nobody knows for sure.

05:55.856 --> 05:57.392
Nobody's ever met him.

05:57.566 --> 06:00.353
Somehow the appeals
make their way to the Judge,

06:00.527 --> 06:05.362
he reviews the case, and if he thinks
you're innocent, he evens the score.

06:05.740 --> 06:11.576
If freedom or life were taken unfairly,
he demands the same in return.

06:11.788 --> 06:14.621
An eye for an eye.

06:23.800 --> 06:25.961
Reddington says Mark Hastings
was held captive?

06:26.177 --> 06:29.635
Yes, but not by Reynoso.
He thinks it might've been payback

06:29.806 --> 06:32.548
for a different case
Hastings prosecuted 12 years ago.

06:32.726 --> 06:34.262
Aram.

06:34.436 --> 06:38.349
Leonard Debs, sentenced to 14 years
for armed robbery when he was 28.

06:38.523 --> 06:41.014
According to this so-called Judge,
this guy's innocent?

06:41.192 --> 06:44.730
A witness allegedly came fonNard
at the time saying Debs
wasn't at the scene.

06:44.905 --> 06:46.361
Hastings never told the defense.

06:47.949 --> 06:50.065
He served 12 years
of his 14-year sentence.

06:50.243 --> 06:52.108
Hastings went missing
12 years ago.

06:52.287 --> 06:55.779
Hastings took 12 years from
Leonard Debs, so the Judge
evened the score.

06:55.957 --> 06:57.913
And Reddington says
there have been others.

06:58.084 --> 07:00.746
A New York homicide detective,
an appellate courtjudge,

07:00.921 --> 07:03.663
two prosecutors,
all missing and presumed dead.

07:03.840 --> 07:06.673
All involved in cases in which
some impropriety was alleged,

07:06.843 --> 07:08.674
which made them targets
for the Judge.

07:08.845 --> 07:10.210
An underground
criminal court of appeals.

07:10.388 --> 07:12.674
We believe the appeals
are processed

07:12.849 --> 07:15.682
through a book depository
run by a prison literacy project.

07:15.852 --> 07:18.719
We pulled the files of everyone
who worked at the depository

07:18.897 --> 07:21.058
and I think we found something.
Frank Gordon.

07:21.232 --> 07:23.939
A civilian now,
but he's a convicted killer.

07:24.110 --> 07:26.146
He now works
for a prison literacy project

07:26.321 --> 07:28.482
at their book depository
in Monroe, Virginia.

07:28.657 --> 07:32.241
He takes the letters from the returned
books, screens them for the Judge.

07:32.702 --> 07:33.691
Find him

07:33.870 --> 07:35.986
and see if you can
get anything out of him.

07:39.250 --> 07:41.832
Frank's been with us
for almost six years now,

07:42.003 --> 07:44.745
ever since the court
reversed his conviction.

07:45.465 --> 07:48.047
Does his job require
he interact with prisoners?

07:48.218 --> 07:52.336
Well, not directly, but he does
respond to their requests.

07:52.514 --> 07:57.634
Our program is one of the many
that provides inmates
with reading materials.

07:58.895 --> 08:00.931
Frank?

08:06.653 --> 08:08.268
Who else knows Frank
stays here?

08:08.780 --> 08:12.773
Is he in some kind of trouble?
What's back there?

08:12.951 --> 08:15.317
I really feel we should wait
for Frank to come back.

08:15.495 --> 08:18.032
It's his space. It's--

08:18.623 --> 08:20.454
[m1

08:21.543 --> 08:22.578
Stay here.

08:24.421 --> 08:25.911
Hello?

08:30.844 --> 08:35.133
Mr. Gordon, FBI,
we'd like to talk to you.

08:40.645 --> 08:42.636
[CLATTERING]

08:42.897 --> 08:46.264
LIZ: What is it?
RESSLER: Stay where you are.

09:09.257 --> 09:12.249
LIZ:
Ressler? You okay?

09:13.678 --> 09:15.464
Ressler.

09:16.514 --> 09:17.799
[GUNSHOTS]

09:21.269 --> 09:22.349
WOMAN:
He was just there.

09:22.562 --> 09:25.178
Agent Keen, she fired,
tried to stop him.

09:25.356 --> 09:27.893
But it happened too fast. He got away.

09:28.068 --> 09:30.480
I set up checkpoints
at all major roads and highways.

09:30.653 --> 09:32.689
Sent Frank Gordon's photo
to state, federal.

09:32.864 --> 09:34.479
You're not gonna believe this.

09:34.657 --> 09:39.117
Pleas from inmates, all handwritten,
from prisons all over the country.

09:39.287 --> 09:42.529
ADX, Marion, Pelican Bay.
And look at this.

09:42.957 --> 09:44.743
Alan Ray Rifkin.

09:44.918 --> 09:46.533
It's a case folder.

09:46.711 --> 09:48.121
Research, evidence.

09:48.296 --> 09:50.582
Frank's reviewing trial transcripts
for the Judge.

09:52.300 --> 09:54.336
Alan Ray Rifkin,
American college student.

09:54.511 --> 09:57.298
Dropped out, joined the Army.
Deployed to Afghanistan.

09:57.472 --> 09:58.962
In 2003, he was tried

09:59.140 --> 10:00.926
and convicted
as an enemy combatant.

10:01.101 --> 10:02.762
Fought alongside the Taliban.

10:03.144 --> 10:04.930
He's scheduled for execution
tomorrow.

10:05.313 --> 10:06.598
According to the charges,

10:06.773 --> 10:08.559
Rifkin and a few dozen
Taliban fighters

10:08.733 --> 10:11.816
raided an Afghan village
killing dozens of civilians.

10:12.028 --> 10:13.939
At trial, Rifkin's lawyers
claimed

10:14.114 --> 10:17.948
it was friendly fire, that
the American military
destroyed the village from the air,

10:18.118 --> 10:20.234
mistaking it for a Taliban outpost.

10:20.620 --> 10:24.238
The military denied it.
If the Judge thinks Rifkin is innocent--

10:24.415 --> 10:26.667
ARAM:
Guys, that Rifkin case
you were asking about?

10:27.252 --> 10:31.416
The investigating officer was the senior
FBI agent in Afghanistan at the time.

10:32.757 --> 10:33.963
Harold Cooper.

10:34.676 --> 10:36.041
COOPER:
Think this is a coincidence?

10:36.219 --> 10:39.507
Reddington feeds you the Judge
and I'm next on that lunatic's hit list?

10:39.681 --> 10:41.763
We need to take it seriously.
No, we don't.

10:41.933 --> 10:44.299
The federal prosecutor
on the case is Tom Connally.

10:44.477 --> 10:47.059
His reputation speaks for itself,
so should mine.

10:47.230 --> 10:49.937
Rifkin admitted to treason.
We're not saying he's innocent.

10:50.108 --> 10:52.190
But if you or Connally
are in danger--

10:52.360 --> 10:54.726
What does this so-called Judge
think that we missed?

10:54.904 --> 10:57.236
We don't know yet.
We're reviewing the file now.

10:57.407 --> 10:59.944
Fine, you do what you need to do.

11:00.118 --> 11:02.575
But I'm telling you,
Alan Ray Rifkin is guilty.

11:03.371 --> 11:07.455
And | for one will lose no sleep
watching him pay the ultimate price
for his crimes.

11:12.005 --> 11:14.872
Mr. Rifkin, my name is Agent Keen.
I'm with the FBI.

11:15.049 --> 11:18.132
Oh, l'd stand and applaud but...
Alan, be nice.

11:18.303 --> 11:21.841
I'm sorry, but I was told Mr. Rifkin
had waived all representation.

11:22.015 --> 11:24.427
He has, all of his legal claims
have been exhausted.

11:24.642 --> 11:26.678
Then you are?
Oh, Ruth Kipling.

11:26.895 --> 11:28.931
The Amnesty Collective.

11:29.105 --> 11:31.721
The capital guidelines state
that death-row inmates

11:31.900 --> 11:34.312
are allowed a designated
spiritual advisor.

11:37.030 --> 11:38.816
Okay.

11:40.992 --> 11:44.155
First, let me tell you that
I'm not here to reconsider
yourcase.

11:44.329 --> 11:47.492
The court rulings are final--
How's this work, Agent Keen?

11:47.665 --> 11:49.166
You just assume that I'm stupid?

11:49.334 --> 11:52.701
I'm not here to see if you're stupid.
I'm here to see if you're angry.

11:52.879 --> 11:54.494
Angry enough to want revenge.

11:54.672 --> 11:57.960
It's my understanding you filed for
a demand ofjustice with the Judge.

11:58.134 --> 12:00.375
As I said, all of his
legal appeals have been--

12:00.553 --> 12:02.054
He knows what I mean.

12:03.765 --> 12:06.723
Since when does the FBI believe
in prison-yard myths?

12:06.893 --> 12:08.849
[m1

12:09.020 --> 12:12.683
It's a story. He doesn't exist.

12:12.899 --> 12:14.389
Here's what I will say.

12:14.567 --> 12:17.650
l have a sacred duty
to battle the evil that put me here.

12:18.488 --> 12:21.525
And who put you here?
You read his file, you know he confessed.

12:21.699 --> 12:23.781
I assure you,
not of my own free will.

12:24.285 --> 12:28.028
You're saying you were coerced?
I'm saying that l was beaten.

12:28.665 --> 12:32.874
I'm saying that FBI agent,
Harold Cooper, he beat me.

12:33.711 --> 12:38.501
Under the orders of Assistant
US. Attorney Thomas Connally.

12:41.010 --> 12:43.001
[ANNOUNCER SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY ON TV]

12:45.348 --> 12:48.135
JOLENE:
What's the story with guys
and basketball anyway?

12:48.309 --> 12:51.472
If the Wizards were playing,
I could stand in front of my TV naked

12:51.646 --> 12:53.637
and you know what
my fiance would say?

12:53.940 --> 12:55.805
Move.
Really?

12:56.234 --> 12:59.601
BARTENDER: Ma'am?
Makers, double.

12:59.821 --> 13:02.358
She's having an affair
with Mr. Whitney.

13:02.532 --> 13:05.820
Have you talked to him about it?
l have. Believe me, it's not good.

13:05.994 --> 13:08.155
Especially during
parent-teacher conferences

13:08.329 --> 13:10.411
Oh...
because her husband has no clue.

13:10.581 --> 13:13.072
But, you know, that's the job.

13:13.251 --> 13:17.369
I mean, teachers get to know every part
of their students' lives, their families.

13:18.715 --> 13:21.548
Some of it you just have to
keep secret.

13:21.759 --> 13:23.590
[JAZZ MUSIC
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

13:23.803 --> 13:25.839
Are you good at that?

13:27.348 --> 13:28.758
At what?

13:30.435 --> 13:31.845
Keeping secrets.

13:36.357 --> 13:40.316
Where's your wife?
She couldn't come.

13:41.404 --> 13:44.316
Did you invite her?
I thought...

13:44.532 --> 13:46.614
I thought you had a fiancé.
Oh, I do.

13:46.826 --> 13:48.532
We haven't picked a date yet.

13:48.745 --> 13:52.454
l'd invite you to the wedding
but I don't think he'd like you.

13:53.499 --> 13:55.876
Why is that?
Isn't it obvious?

13:56.419 --> 14:00.207
You, here, buying me drinks
while your wife's back home.

14:01.257 --> 14:03.714
I haven't done anything wrong.

14:07.096 --> 14:09.087
[m1

14:17.065 --> 14:19.056
Oh, my God. Ha.

14:20.693 --> 14:22.433
Hi.

14:23.404 --> 14:25.395
[CHUCKLING]

14:27.075 --> 14:29.441
Oh, my God.
Oh, my God.

14:30.203 --> 14:31.443
Oh, God.

14:32.372 --> 14:34.328
I'm sorry.

14:34.582 --> 14:36.322
I'm sorry.

14:40.880 --> 14:41.915
Yeah, me too.

14:51.891 --> 14:53.222
You know, actually,
I'm not that sorry.

14:53.393 --> 14:55.384
[m1

14:55.812 --> 14:57.052
Room 618.

15:03.986 --> 15:05.021
[SIGHS]

15:07.532 --> 15:11.070
Yeah, I'm there now.
Where are we on the Rifkin case?

15:11.244 --> 15:13.530
Understood. But I need to know
you and your men

15:13.704 --> 15:15.865
will be ready to grab
Connally and Cooper

15:16.040 --> 15:18.076
if the execution goes down
as scheduled.

15:18.251 --> 15:20.617
Okay, bye.
KlPLlNG: Damn FBI.

15:20.795 --> 15:23.377
Couldn't find their own asses
with a mirror and a GPS.

15:23.548 --> 15:25.789
How the hell did they find you?
I don't know.

15:25.967 --> 15:28.333
Somebody must be talking
and it's certainly not me.

15:28.511 --> 15:30.217
Oh, Frank, I believe you.

15:30.388 --> 15:32.470
You're a John, not a Judas.

15:32.682 --> 15:34.673
Walk with me, it's feeding time.

15:35.685 --> 15:37.300
[m1

15:37.478 --> 15:39.469
[PEOPLE GROANING
AND COUGHING]

15:44.610 --> 15:46.316
Hastings,
the one we released,

15:46.487 --> 15:48.728
do we know if he's
talking to the authorities?

15:48.906 --> 15:51.192
He's not.
His mind's too far gone.

15:51.367 --> 15:52.573
My sources say he's with

15:52.743 --> 15:54.699
his family,
still hasn't spoken a word.

15:55.830 --> 15:58.446
Oh, it's just a matter
of time.

15:58.666 --> 16:02.329
About the Rifkin execution,
we're ready to respond but...

16:03.254 --> 16:05.461
Yeah, but what?

16:08.134 --> 16:10.967
Frank. Frank. Look at me.

16:11.345 --> 16:13.722
You were innocent.

16:13.931 --> 16:16.593
People like this put you in jail.

16:16.809 --> 16:18.891
They took 20 years of your life.

16:19.103 --> 16:22.015
Thirty from my father.
But if they're onto us?

16:22.190 --> 16:24.522
If they find us, so be it.

16:24.734 --> 16:28.101
Until then, I'm not gonna stop
the work we're doing.

16:29.572 --> 16:33.906
If Rifkin dies, tell the others
to carry out the sentence.

16:35.453 --> 16:39.366
Just because you're on the outside
now doesn't mean you can forget.

16:42.376 --> 16:44.458
Good night, Mother.

16:47.673 --> 16:51.461
Okay, so the question is, why does
the Judge think Rifkin is innocent?

16:51.636 --> 16:54.594
We put together a timeline of events
using the file you found

16:54.764 --> 16:57.130
in Frank Gordon's room,
and we found a problem.

16:57.308 --> 16:58.514
After Rifkin was caught,

16:58.684 --> 17:01.642
Cooper had him flown from Bagram
to Andrews Air Force Base.

17:01.812 --> 17:05.396
From there, a prison transport took
them to a federal facility in Alexandria.

17:05.566 --> 17:07.602
That trip should have taken
30 minutes.

17:07.777 --> 17:11.520
At trial, the US. marshal supervising
the transport said it arrived on schedule.

17:11.697 --> 17:13.483
RESSLER:
But look at this, it's an event log.

17:13.658 --> 17:16.525
lt recorded the actual time
the marshal swiped into Alexandria.

17:20.623 --> 17:22.284
Why wasn't this presented
at trial?

17:22.500 --> 17:23.706
Another event log was.

17:23.918 --> 17:25.954
One that matched
the 30-minute timeline.

17:26.128 --> 17:27.959
One of the event logs is fake.

17:28.130 --> 17:29.256
[m1

17:29.423 --> 17:33.382
We should find the marshal,
ask him directly.

17:41.060 --> 17:42.596
LIZ:
William Munson?

17:43.312 --> 17:45.644
Agent Keen, FBI.
I'm investigating a case

17:45.815 --> 17:47.351
you're connected to.

